# Naming, Language, and Routes (CRITICAL)

Follow these three layers in every change. Do not mix languages in the wrong layer.

## 1. Source code — English only

Write **only in English** in source files:

- Identifiers: variables, functions, methods, classes, types, interfaces, enums/constants names
- File and directory names (e.g. `create-supabase-server-client.ts`, `stock-page.tsx`)
- React component names in PascalCase in English (e.g. `DashboardLayout`, not `PainelLayout` — the **route** can still be `/painel`)
- Comments and JSDoc/TSDoc
- Commit messages and internal technical docs in the repo (unless the team standard says otherwise)

Do not use Portuguese (or other languages) for code identifiers or comments.

## 2. Routes (URLs) — Portuguese only

Path segments visible in the browser must be **Portuguese**, lowercase, kebab-case when multi-word:

- Examples: `/painel`, `/estoque`, `/contato`, `/veiculo`, `/veiculo/[slug]`
- Redirects, `href`, `redirect()`, middleware matchers, and sitemap routes must use these Portuguese paths

English path segments (e.g. `/dashboard`, `/inventory`) are not allowed unless an explicit exception is documented.

## 3. User-facing interface — Portuguese only

All copy the end user sees must be **Portuguese**:

- Visible text, labels, placeholders, buttons, headings, empty states, errors shown in UI
- `aria-label`, `title`, and similar when intended for users
- Validation messages and toasts intended for the user

English is allowed in developer-only logs and non-user-facing telemetry, not in UI strings.

## Quick check

| Layer            | Language   |
|------------------|------------|
| Code & comments  | English    |
| URL paths        | Portuguese |
| UI copy          | Portuguese |
